<h2>Problem #1: You Don't Own Anything</h2>
<p>Every SaaS landing page builder — Carrd, Typedream, Dorik, Framer — hosts your site on their platform. Your landing page lives on their servers, in their editor, under their control.</p>

<p>What happens if:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>They raise prices?</strong> You pay or lose your site.</li>
<li><strong>They shut down?</strong> Your landing page disappears.</li>
<li><strong>You want to leave?</strong> You can't export your design. You rebuild from scratch.</li>
<li><strong>They change features?</strong> Your page breaks or loses functionality.</li>
</ul>

<p>This is the <strong>platform lock-in trap</strong>. You're renting, not buying. And rent never stops.</p>

<h2>Problem #2: You Still Have to Build It</h2>
<p>"But Carrd has templates!" Sure. Basic ones. And you still need to:</p>
<ol>
<li>Pick a template (from limited options)</li>
<li>Customize every section</li>
<li>Write all the copy</li>
<li>Choose colors, fonts, spacing</li>
<li>Make it responsive</li>
<li>Set up forms, analytics, custom domains</li>
</ol>

<p>This takes hours. If you're not a designer, it shows. And if you want something that looks professional? You'll spend days.</p>

<p><strong>ZOO templates are different.</strong> They're conversion-engineered by design. The copy structure is built in. The layout is optimized for SaaS, startups, and digital products. You customize colors and text — not layout and structure.</p>

<h2>Problem #3: The Annual Cost Is Deceptive</h2>
<p>$15/month sounds reasonable. It's "just" $15. But let's do the math:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Typedream Launch:</strong> $15 × 12 = <span class="price-bad">$180/year</span></li>
<li><strong>Typedream Business:</strong> $49 × 12 = <span class="price-bad">$588/year</span></li>
<li><strong>Dorik Premium:</strong> $39 × 12 = <span class="price-bad">$468/year</span></li>
<li><strong>Framer Pro (per editor):</strong> $20 × 12 = <span class="price-bad">$240/year</span></li>
</ul>

<p>Over 3 years, that's $540–$1,764 for a LANDING PAGE. A single page. That you don't even own.</p>

<p>Meanwhile, ZOO landing page templates cost <strong>$29 once</strong>. Use them for 1 year or 10 years. Still $29.</p>

<h2>When SaaS Builders Make Sense (And When They Don't)</h2>
<p>We're not saying SaaS builders are bad. They serve a purpose. But they're not the right tool for every job.</p>

<h3>✅ SaaS builders make sense when:</h3>
<ul>
<li>You need a complex multi-page website</li>
<li>You want built-in CMS for non-technical team members</li>
<li>You need advanced animations and interactions</li>
<li>You're building a web app, not a landing page</li>
</ul>

<h3>❌ SaaS builders DON'T make sense when:</h3>
<ul>
<li>You just need a landing page (use templates)</li>
<li>You want to own your code (use templates)</li>
<li>You're cost-conscious (templates are 90%+ cheaper)</li>
<li>You want to host anywhere (templates work everywhere)</li>
<li>You need to ship fast (templates = hours, not days)</li>
</ul>

